This paper is primarily focused on visual object recognition, which falls under the computer vision (cs.CV) sub-category. The paper also proposes a biologically inspired model for context-aware object recognition, which involves machine learning and artificial intelligence (cs.AI). The model is trained to approximate human-level performance, which suggests that it may involve techniques from machine learning and deep learning (cs.LG). The paper also describes a series of psychophysics experiments, which suggests that it may involve human-computer interaction (cs.HC). Finally, the paper proposes a novel model architecture that incorporates both object and contextual information, which may involve techniques from neural networks (cs.NE).
